se surname was changed to <i>Bissett</i> (see 2 above) after his immigration to NS, Canada, in 1752."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Bisset was born in 1280, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, E Wilhelmus BISSETT, was 31 and her mother, MRS Wilhelmus BISSETT, was 31. She had at least 2 sons with John de Calcroft."},"et":{"1280–":"1280–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1280–1352":"1280–1352","1309–Male":"1309–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1352":"1352","1250":"1250","1309":"1309","1280":"1280","East Bridgeford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1280–":"1280–Kuollut","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1280–1352":"1280–1352","1309–Male":"1309–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1352":"1352","1250":"1250","1309":"1309","1280":"1280","East Bridgeford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1280–":"1280–Décédée","1280–Female":"1280–Décédée","1280–1352":"1280–1352","1309–Male":"1309–D